<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911226-0063</DOCNO><DOCID>911226-0063.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Israel Plans to Join Treaty   Against Spread of Missiles   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>ISRAEL (ISR)MIDDLE EAST (ML)</RE><LP>   JERUSALEM -- Israel will join an international pactlimiting the spread of missile technology on Dec. 31, theDefense Ministry announced.   The treaty, the Missile Technology Control Regime, was setup by the seven major industrialized nations in 1987 and hasbeen joined since by nine other countries.</LP><TEXT>   A ministry statement said Israel would sign &quot;a newproclamation&quot; controlling exports of missiles or parts ofmissiles that could be used to deliver warheads weighing 500kilograms or that have a range of 300 kilometers.   The move was expected since Israel announced in Octoberthat it expected to sign the treaty, following reports thatthe U.S. was putting pressure on Israel to accept morestringent controls on missile exports.   Parliament's defense and foreign affairs committee onTuesday approved signing the treaty, the Defense Ministrysaid. No other approval is required.</TEXT></DOC>